Background

Texans are currently suffering a winter storm of deadly proportions. Thus far, 37 people have died from weather-related fatalities, 4 million people have lost power, 12 million people have had their water disrupted, and 300 people have been hospitalized for carbon monoxide poisoning. This climate crisis and its deadly impacts have been largely driven by a failure of Texass centralized power grid, a willful neglect of new investment in energy infrastructure, denials of the science of climate change, and the exacerbation of existing structural inequities for BIPOC (Black, Indigenous, People of Color) individuals and families of low income.

We are excited to announce an informal Urban-wide mutual aid donation campaign for Texans affected by the winter storm of 2021. The campaign will be an optional, virtual, and anonymous collection open to all Urban staff from various centers and offices to donate what they can from their own personal funds. We will be recording and tracking all of our donations on this website, so check back for updates.

We have chosen to direct all proceeds raised from this campaign to mutual aid groups in Texas, because they have been one of the most flexible and fastest ways for immediate needs to be met during the winter storm. For example, when there was no coordinated plan to assist house-less people prepare for the dropping temperatures, mutual aid groups were the first to pay for their hotel rooms, drive to shelters, and pay for food.

This campaign will begin on Friday, February 19th, and close on February 26th. You can read a more about the background of the crisis, the conditions that led to it, and a bit of background of mutual aid organizations here.

How to donate?

You can donate in two ways:

  1. You can send donations via venmo to your Centers point person (See table below)/ Make sure to include Mutual aid [Your Center/Office] in the subject line of your donation to be included in your centers count.

  2. You can also directly donate to any organization supporting people who are in need during the climate crisis and send the receipt to your Centers point person (See table below). Make sure to include Mutual aid [Your Center/Office] in the email subject line, so your contribution can be included in your centers count! Extra fun if your emailed receipts include a description of the organization or person conducting the support.

If your center/office is not listed, please consider representing your center/office. Reach out to jjagannath@urban.org and storresrod@urban.org if you can volunteer, and we will get you plugged in!

Where is the money going?

We plan on evenly splitting our raised funds between the following mutual aid organizations, chosen via group consensus and the input of our staff familiar with Texas. Because the situation is rapidly evolving on the ground, and because mutual aid organizations are often limited in capacity (and may request to redirect funds), this list will not be finalized until sometime closer to the end of the competition:

  • Austin: Austin Mutual Aid, Stop the Sweeps Austin, Free Lunch Austin
  • Corpus Christi: Corpus Christi Mutual Aid
  • Dallas: Feed the People Dallas, Dallas Stops Evictions, Lucha Dallas
  • Houston: Houseless Organizing Coalition, Crowdsource Rescue, Say Her Name Texas
  • Rio Grande Valley: Rio Grande Valley Mutual Aid
  • San Antonio: Black Futures Collective, Para Mi Gente Mutual Aid
  • Immigrant specific: LaUnidad11
  • Jail and Commissary Account Support: Texas Jail Project

In the event we need to add or change organizations (sometimes organizations reach funding capacity and request that funds be sent elsewhere) we will reference public resources, such as the ones listed below:

  • TX Mutual Aid Directory
  • Texas Weather Crisis Resource Doc
  • Twitter List

More ways to help

The Texas Jail Project is asking people to donate funds to the commissary accounts of folks trapped in Texas jails without heat or water and with diminishing supplies of food. Your donations will be reimbursed later by the Texas Jail Project, if you like, but they really need people to log in and make the donations because there are limits on how many donations a single person can make each day to accounts for incarcerated people.

I am forwarding a note from our friends at the Texas Jail Project, who are in need of some critical support getting money into folks commissary accounts. As youre all probably aware, Texas is freezing over and people have been without power, food, and heat for days now. As we know in these kinds of crises, conditions inside jails and prisons are that much more unlivable. Commissary helps people get edible food, clean water, warmer clothes, and meet other immediate needs. The Texas Connect network system via which funds are sent only allows up to three commissary payments per day per person, so as many hands on deck who can help distribute funds, the better! TX Jail Project will fully reimburse via PayPal or Venmo once they get through survival mode this week.

More specific directions in this spreadsheet, and please forward to any of your friends, family, members, partners etc. who can afford to send some cash without immediate reimbursement at this time.
